segments.text: to be a court reporter in the Navy.
I did steno mask, and then I would have to take that, put the earphones on and type it all up.
It's a mess.
Does she have to listen to it?
Does she have earphones on?
Yeah, I used to do that.
I used to have these court marshals and
You were talking about Calhoun.
Oh yes, Stately.
I think Stately was the word.
But he was also very available.
Did you all think A&M was making progress during those days?
Oh, I thought it was just going.
I thought I was involved in the greatest development of any school in history.
Well, I think a lot of people felt that way.
The schools up north were declining.
This was almost a renaissance.
The student body was growing in number.
What about the quality?
Oh, yes.
I think the women were helping that, too.
Well, very fine.
Do you remember any changes in the way you all did things with women?
Did that affect the way— No, I don't remember any problem with political correctness or that kind of thing.
We were just natural.
I think everybody was very respectful of women.
What about minorities?
Do you remember when you first had some black students?
Yes, I didn't have very many.
That was hard.
I mean, I was different.
Most of my students were typical Anglo-Saxon.
I remember that we tutored the football team a couple of times.
Describe that.
Well, it was volunteer for the students.
I thought if I could develop their vocabulary, this would help.
So I built Greek and Latin roots and added suffixes and tried to make football stories out of it.
I'm not sure that I developed many new words for them, but vocabulary is what I wanted.
The football players were all very respectful.
I had one student, I remember his name was Lord.
Do you remember?
Lord was one of our outstanding football players.
He used to call me and say, this is the Lord speaking.
But he was always being carried off the field, and I would groan.
He won't be in class for a while now.
But the students at the football tutoring were very nice, just like anyone else.
But I'm not sure I grabbed them with vocabulary.
Did, in your doing that, did the athletic department ask for, did anyone from athletics ever ask you to give special treatment to any student?
No one ever did.
And they did when I was at Lycoming College.
But no one ever did, and they would come around and see if they needed any help with them or if they were attending class.
It was all very professional.
In all of your years here, did anyone in authority, real or self-appointed authority, ever try to influence the grade you gave anyone?
No.
No politician, no board member, no Rich Aggie?
No, I can't think of any problem with that at all.
Now, when I was at Brooklyn College, I remember students saying if I didn't give them an A, they would go to Vietnam, things like that.
But I'm sure that there were incidents where they didn't agree with my grade.
I don't recall any outside pressure.
By the end of the 70s, were you still teaching primarily undergraduate courses?
By the end of the 70s, almost all graduate courses.
Describe how that's different.
Well, it's much easier in a way.
The classes are smaller.
I didn't have any of these ninety classes.
I didn't like a small class either.
If it was under twelve, that was too small.
But the classes were smaller.
But of course, most of my graduate classes were three hours, so I needed to develop different techniques for changing the pace.
They would meet once a week for three hours.
The summer session they would meet three hours every day, which put a little pressure on, but it was
they were learning.
Three hours once a week, you have to spend a while warming them up each time.
But that was the difference.
length of the class, but the students were a smaller number of students.
These, by and large, were students already had an undergraduate degree in what?
All different fields, from physics to English.
They were all different fields, and many of them had been teaching for a few years, and the master's degree would help them salary-wise and professionally.
So this was not primarily for them to be certified.
They already were certified.
No, no.
Most of this.
I think that, if I'm not mistaken,
Most of them were certified.
They could take it without certification.
And geographically they were from?
All over.
I had some students traveling from San Antonio.
But they were basically from Texas?
Oh, yes.
Yes, there were.
Well, I've had some students from other states, but I think they were here permanently for the
More women than men.
More women than men.
Almost no international students.
You know, I had international students from Afghanistan, China.
Would this have been true in the early 80s?
Yes.
I had many foreign students, and I still have trophies around the house where they gave me things.
I found out later that when you invite them over to your home, they think they have to bring you something.
I remember a student begging me not to invite him over anymore, and I didn't want him to give things.
What were some of the unusual or distinctive gifts that you remember they brought?
Well, I remember a tea set.
Now this was just, I mean, and beautifully lacquered and things of that sort.
And then wall hangings and some of those scroll paintings from China.
But I didn't realize until later that that was their custom.
But yes, we, from the very beginning, had international students, many of them from Afghanistan, I mean, Iran.
And when I taught the cultural foundation, which was a master's level course, it was interesting that so many of these Muslim women felt sorry for American women.
And I assume it was because American women had to work.
But our vision of these Muslim women is that they're terribly handicapped as far as freedom is concerned.
They didn't seem to worry about it.
Well, that was the impression I got, or they would tell me, about their culture.
In terms of their capability, can you compare the norm for the U.S. national students with the norm for the international?
Yes, I think quite definitely there is a difference, and the more oriental student was a very good memorizer.
And some of these from Vietnam, they were very conscientious and very good memorizers, but they didn't always have the creative mind that some of our students had.
What about their diligence?
Well, I think that was all over on the Asian side.
Although our students generally worked hard, but many of them had teaching and other responsibilities.
Did you have any Western Hemisphere international students?
Well, I've had some from Mexico and Venezuela.
I had a very fine student from Venezuela.
Compare those Western Hemisphere international students to the Asian.
I don't think they were quite as good memorizers, but I don't have a big sample there.
I think they were all good students, though.
Did you have to do anything special in a graduate course that had some U.S. nationals and some international students?
Well, with the cultural foundations of education, I developed cultural patterns.
I was trying to teach our people what our own culture was as well as how to take these cultural patterns and compare them with different and learn how to compare and develop cultural understanding.
So some of these people would share their cultural differences.
from language all the way down to various hierarchies of values into artifacts.
But I don't know that I can say there was a big difference there.
Most of these graduate students, be they U.S. or international, they were how far out of undergraduate years?
Well, some had been out for a long time.
You're talking about just the international students?
Well, either.
Most of them had been out.
I had some that just went from undergraduate right in, but we kind of discouraged that.
I thought they should be teaching.
Most of these had real experience.
Yes, but some of them had been out for many years.
I had one student who finally sued the university for prejudice against older people because he didn't pass a couple of courses.
But it turns out he hadn't turned any of his work in either.
But there was a wide range.
I think the doctoral level students had had were, of course, definitely farther removed.
But the master's level, some would go right in from the undergraduate.
And those I took to Europe for the comparative ed course.
Half of them had just finished their undergraduate.
Describe one of those trips to Europe.
I only made two.
The first was 1982.
We made arrangements.
It's an awful lot of work to do, of course.
I think we had about 30 or more students.
We got a grant from Conoco to help defray the expenses.
So it cost, as I recall, about $800.
Most of that was just airfare in those days, $82.
We went to London.
and had arrangements to visit all levels of schools in and around London.
And we went to Oxford and looked through the schools there.
Then we went to Stirling, spent about half our time in Stirling, Scotland, and then moved out, took students to all levels of schools and compared them with American schools.
In 1982, I think, the Falkland War was on and we were
getting involved with some of the political discussions there that many of them didn't think we were doing enough to help England.
Then I was there in 84, which was the 40th anniversary of D-Day.
I think Reagan was there and a few others.
We didn't get to interview them.
Do you remember any goofy things that happened on either of those trips?
Well, there was always a problem.
They thought this was more of a tour, and they wanted to see things, and I sympathized with that, wanted to give them as much time.
We had a heart attack, an older woman, and she got into one of the British systems.
They had a student who had a kidney stone attack.
The medical facilities there were better, they thought, than over here, and they actually got time to talk to doctors.
Any goofy things?
Goofy.
Nobody got too drunk?
No.
I didn't see any of that.
I do know that the second time I took my son, who was a student at Clemson,
And we shared the same room.
After the first day, I never saw him.
I was asleep before he ever got in.
I'm not just sure what they were doing.
They were out doing things.
I can't recall anything really.
Nobody lost their entire bag?
We didn't have any problems of that sort.
I do recall, this is not too funny, but in my cultural patterns would be ways of doing this, this, this, and I also had ways of courting and sex, sexual mores.
I think one of the students went to one of the
English professors at the university and asked about his sexual patterns.
And she said, well, Dr. Campbell asked me to do that.
By this time, you're directing theses and dissertations.
Oh, yes.
And I think I was on, one time I was on 50 when I had to start listing them because I would have them at the early stages and they needed to get a committee together.
That was a big thing at our department.
When did the doctoral program begin?
Do you remember?
Well, let's see.
We were approved of the
The Ed.D.
was approved.
We had the Ph.D., I think, earlier.
But my memory is not good.
It may have been in the late seventies or early eighties, but I would have to check on that.
Do you remember some of the first doctoral students you directed?
Well, Barry Thompson was on his committee.
Of course, that was
That was the Ph.D. That was about 1971 or 72. Who was his chairman?
Do you remember?
No.
I think he started out with this man that I can't think of who was a colleague there of Dean Huber.
But Glenn Johnson was on the committee, and I was
asked to get in on that because somebody couldn't meet the defense.
So I was not in on the total thing, but he became chancellor.
What was he doing then?
He was teaching.
He was a very young man.
He may have been down at Pan American or something of that sort, but this was early in the stages.
But your question was who were some of the people that I had?
I can't take credit for the fine things that he did.
I'm not sure.
I think his dissertation had something to do with junior colleges or some aspect.
Of course, Miss Scobie, you know, the wife of the astronaut who was killed?
Oh, yes, yes.
She was in several of my classes.
Do you remember, have any idea how many masters and PhDs you directed?
Yes.
Or doctoral degrees, either Ed.D.
or Ph.D.
The Ed.D.
or Ph.D., I think I only directed about eight.
But I think I was on so many as the bridesmaid.
What's the difference really in a Ph.D. in education and an Ed.D.
in education?
Well, originally it was the language requirement.
And then we replaced the language requirement with statistics.
And I think the Ed.D.
did not require statistics.
We also had the M.A.
and the M.E.D., and the M.A.
required a thesis, and the M.E.D.
did not, but it required some extra coursework.
But the Ed.D.
required a dissertation.
Oh, yes, and there was not any difference.
Really?
In terms of future professional advantage, which was the better degree for the person to get?
Well, when I was at Columbia, they said the EdD was better.
But I always think the Ph.D. is better.
It goes a longer tradition.
That would have been my guess.
Yes.
But there was a time when they thought that EdD was more specialized.
Which was, in terms of the number of students in the years that you spent here, which was more popular?
I think the Ph.D. was still the most popular, and they would take the statistics rather than the foreign language.
All right, you all moved over to the, did you move from the academic to the Harrington building?
Yes.
Describe where the department and the college was put when that moved here.
Well, our department, the curriculum and instruction, I think originally was on the fifth floor.
A few years later we were moved to the third floor.
But I remember when we were on the fifth floor, the fire department came and I saw the chief sweating and mumbling to himself.
He thought it was a fire trap.
Then we moved to the third floor.
I don't know if it's so we'd be safer, but that was curriculum and instruction.
I think Ed Add mainly had the second floor, and then of course Dean Hubert and the Dean of Liberal Arts were up on the eighth floor.
Now, who else, what other education departments were in the Harrington building?
Oh, education.
We had everything except industrial ed and PE and agriculture.
Oh, and ag ed.
Yeah, ag ed was not there.
The others were there, and we also had the English department, I think, and then the history department was there later.
I believe they stayed over at academic, didn't they, for a while, but they later took over the
Yeah.
As far as you were concerned, describe your office.
Well, every office I had had a window, which was nice.
The old academic building, I didn't have a window.
Marvelous facilities.
And of course the computer came in.
I think, I can't remember exactly what it was, but I was going to resist it to the grave.
But then they brought them in and put them in our office.
What kind of instruction was there?
Well, we didn't have very much.
We did have a day or two of it, and it was just beyond me.
I didn't take it seriously.
So mainly it was self-taught, and we had IBM clones.
But if I had had the computer from my earlier stages, I probably could have
stayed teaching longer.
I wouldn't have worn myself out.
I had files.
I was just climbing the walls and I was using the floor.
But the computer was coming in in my last years.
Now, prior to the computer, you had been typing everything?
An electric typewriter.
Of course, in the Navy I had been a court reporter and I was typing all the time.
So typing was my thing.
And your compensation was all from the university, so you didn't have many grants?
I never got a grant, except this conical for the... And so you didn't have many graduate assistants to help you do your research?
No.
I made a few proposals, about two or three proposals, which were never granted.
But my field, of course, is not one that attracts a lot of interest for grants like reading and other bread and butter kinds of courses.
As you all move over into that building in the 80s, were there any key additions to the departmental faculty?
Well, we were keenly growing.
But there's a kid's story about that new building.
which may or may not be true.
But where we had the early childhood room, they had a sandbox.
And I believe that became notorious around the university that the College of Education had installed a sandbox in its
I don't remember ever seeing the sandbox, but we did have the early childhood there.
There were, as I recall, a few bats that remained in the building that had been there in that older building.
But the transition, we moved from different floors a couple of times, as I say, from the fifth curriculum instruction went to the third.
There were adjustments in moving around, but it was a marvelous facility.
Faculty additions, key.
Who were some new colleagues?
Dave Armstrong, who later became a dean of education in North Carolina, was one of our very fine young men.
There were some, you know, my memory is lapsing.
I can't even remember certain philosophers anymore.
Oh, Donna Norton, of course, came when we were in the new building, and she is outstanding in children's literature.
How were women faculty members treated in that department?
I think they were treated just fine.
Can I give a little anecdote?
Please.
Oh, more anecdotes than that.
We had a dean.
She did a nice job, but she called all the men in one time.
This was about the time I was—this is not Dean Hubert.
It's the Lady Dean.
seemed to indicate that we were not treating women right, and we were not told what happened, and she just wanted to make sure that there wouldn't be none of that.
There must have been some reason for her doing that, but it kind of turned some of us off to be called in like little boys.
It turns out that I think someone had disagreed with a woman in a faculty meeting, and you're not supposed to disagree, I guess.
But I've always thought everything was very good.
But I opened doors for women, and I guess that was probably not good either.
Do you remember when the first black faculty member came in?
Yes.
Well, of course, we had Vi Flores, who is now dean at New Mexico.
She was Mexican-American.
And she worked with the dean of the president, I think, Vi Flores.
She was one of the first minorities, just a lovely person.
This lady, she's still there, and her husband is in another department who are black.
Oh gosh, I know her just as well as I can.
And we have several of them now, and I've been on committees, one of them from Africa.
Do you remember any difficulties?
No.
Good.
I can't remember any problem.
Now, if you were to ask some of the women, this might be different.
I do remember one woman
I can't think of her name now, but she was very good.
She said she wanted to be sure she got the same amount of money.
So it could be they were not getting the same amount of money, and I just didn't keep track of that.
But I always thought we had mostly women students.
This is a field where women are leaders.
Did you and your colleagues feel that the college was being treated fairly in the 80s and 90s?
I always did, yes.
And I had experience at a small liberal arts college where most of the departments had more faculty members than majors.
And we were turning out a third or more of the graduates, certifying them, and we had three full-time people.
Now, Glenn Johnson served as department head how long?
Oh, at least five years.
Then who followed him?
Bob Schutz followed him.
We seemed to just wear our department heads out.
It's a big job with all the certification and so on, but Glenn Johnson was getting ill.
Then Bob Schutz took over and he had a heart attack.
Then we had David David and Phil Limbacher.
Well, about Peters, Jim Kroc, a very fine man.
And then I retired about, I think we had,
I'm sorry, her name is so... You retired what year?
But I broke my hip in 89, and I think I went on half time for a while.
All right.
During those years,
What was the primary function of the department head?
What was he or she to do?
That was everything, as far as I could tell.
Of course, I see it from without being the department head, but I think he was responsible for everything.
Under Dean Hubert, I think Dean Hubert kind
said, this is your job, but you report to me.
But I think, like Glenn Johnson and Bob Schutz, they had to do everything.
Now, when Dean Hubert moved up to be chancellor, who followed him as?
Oh, this was, and I was on the committee that selected him.
Was that Dean Corrigan?
Dean Corrigan, wonderful man.
Fairly different style, but very effective.
Describe his manner.
Jolly and very insightful.
I think he knew everything he said.
He could back it up.
He was interested in all areas.
But he was more accessible and congenial.
Dean Hubert was congenial but harsher, kind of.
The surface was a little harder.
Dean Corrigan was very accessible.
And he served until about the time you retired, didn't he?
Yes.
Did the college make good progress during those years, you think?
Oh, yes.
I think more than ever.
I think the visibility, because Dean Corrigan had some
